Typescript does not support type checks for the `Enum` type. You could modify your class to iterate over the enum elements to create a new object. In JavaScript the `Enum` is basically turned into an object.

For example the enum of your example results in
```
(function (sample) {
    sample[sample[&quot;AA&quot;] = 0] = &quot;AA&quot;;
    sample[sample[&quot;BB&quot;] = 1] = &quot;BB&quot;;
    sample[&quot;CC&quot;] = &quot;cc&quot;;
})(sample || (sample = {}));
```

which if executed results in
```
{
  0:    &quot;AA&quot;,
  &quot;AA&quot;: 0,
  1:    &quot;BB&quot;,
  &quot;BB&quot;: 1,
  &quot;cc&quot;: &quot;CC&quot;,
  &quot;CC&quot;: &quot;cc&quot;
}
```

However when iterating over the properies you might not always be able to identify which property was an enum key and which an enum value.

If you somehow solve this problem you could create a new &quot;enum&quot; using the following example code
```
const myEnum = {}
for (let i = 0; i &lt; keys.length; i++) {
    myEnum[i] = keys[i]
}
```
effectively enforcing all enum values to be numeric.

