answers.body_markdown:
This has to do with how `Omit` works. Here&#39;s how it is defined in [`lib.es5.d.ts`](https://github.com/microsoft/TypeScript/blob/038d95144d8b93c2799d1732181c89c3d84362d5/lib/lib.es5.d.ts#L1469):

```typescript
type Omit&lt;T, K extends keyof any&gt; = Pick&lt;T, Exclude&lt;keyof T, K&gt;&gt;;
```

`Exclude&lt;keyof T, K&gt;` produces a union of all keys except the ones you pass as `K`. So in your example that would be `&#39;b&#39; | &#39;c&#39;`.

`Pick` then uses a mapped type to iterate over these keys and create a new object type:

```typescript
type Pick&lt;T, K extends keyof T&gt; = {
    [P in K]: T[P];
};
```

Because of this the type gets &quot;flattened&quot;. In case of `b`, `T[&#39;b&#39;]` returns `true | false | undefined` which TypeScript simplifies to `boolean | undefined`.

And you end up with:

```typescript
type Ommited = {
    b?: boolean | undefined;
    c?: number | undefined;
}
```

---

I think the best thing you can do here is extract the &quot;or&quot; part into a named type and re-use that:

```typescript
type OrPart = {b?:true, c?:never} | {b?:false, c:number}
type WithOr = {a:string} &amp; OrPart
const m1: OrPart = {b: true};
const m2: WithOr = {...m1, a: &#39;a&#39;}
```

[Playground](http://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#code/C4TwDgpgBA8gTgBQIZ2FAvFA3gIwPwBcwcArhADRQDGhAdhAG4RwC+UAPtvgQGZIA2AZwrUCtEgFsczFgChQkKAHUAlsAAW8DNiQFBxFbQDmbAGSxEKYLKoB7WvqgSAjAQvJU23G+JkWAbht7RwkAJjdVDS1MLAA6eJdKXSgAciQUliA)

